---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Our Approach"
  description="Why Australian Home Collective begins with the room, the household and the problem rather than a list of products."
>
  <header class="page-intro">
    <div class="narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow">How we work</p>
      <h1>Our Approach</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        We begin with the household problem, not the shopping list.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="content narrow">
    <p>
      Many home websites start with products. We usually start with the problem.
    </p>
    <p>
      That means asking:
    </p>
    <ul class="feature-list">
      <li>What is actually causing the clutter?</li>
      <li>What space needs to be measured?</li>
      <li>What will block the product from fitting?</li>
      <li>Will it suit a rental?</li>
      <li>Can it be cleaned without becoming another chore?</li>
      <li>Will people actually use it?</li>
      <li>Does the household need to buy anything at all?</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Why we start before the purchase</h2>
    <p>
      A product can be well made and still be wrong for a particular home.
    </p>
    <p>
      It may be too tall for the shelf, too deep for the cupboard, too awkward for a rental,
      too hard to clean, too heavy to move, or too complicated to maintain.
    </p>
    <p>
      The right buying decision often depends on the space, not just the product.
    </p>

    <h2>Real homes are not showrooms</h2>
    <p>
      We are not writing for perfect display homes.
    </p>
    <p>
      The guides are for households with limited bench space, awkward drawers, rental limits,
      busy routines, mismatched containers, deep cupboards and clutter that comes back.
    </p>
    <p>
      If a system takes too much effort to keep going, it is unlikely to last.
    </p>

    <h2>When not buying is the better answer</h2>
    <p>
      Not every household problem needs another product. Sometimes the better first step is to:
    </p>
    <ul class="feature-list">
      <li>remove duplicates</li>
      <li>clear expired pantry items</li>
      <li>match lids to containers</li>
      <li>move rarely used appliances</li>
      <li>group items by use</li>
      <li>measure the space properly</li>
      <li>choose a simpler system</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Buying storage before sorting the problem can make a home feel more crowded, not less.
    </p>

    <h2>How to use the guides</h2>
    <p>
      Find the room or problem that matches yours, note the measurements and drawbacks that
      apply, then decide whether the product would earn its place.
    </p>
    <p>
      The aim is not to buy more. It is to make a sound decision either way.
    </p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
